value.value: Binding to a ubiquitin conjugating enzyme, any of the E2 proteins.
Binding to a ubiquitin protein ligase enzyme, any of the E3 proteins.
Binding to beta-endorphin, a peptide generated by the cleavage of pro-opiomelanocortin.
The process in which linear telomeric DNA is remodeled into duplex loops, by the invasion of a 3' single-stranded overhang into the duplex region.
Binding to an opioid receptor.

label.value: synaptic vesicle fusion to presynaptic active zone membrane

value.value: Fusion of the membrane of a synaptic vesicle with the presynaptic active zone membrane, thereby releasing its cargo neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft.

label.value: regulation of synaptic vesicle fusion to presynaptic active zone membrane

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of synaptic vesicle fusion to the presynaptic membrane.

label.value: negative regulation of synaptic vesicle fusion to presynaptic active zone membrane

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of synaptic vesicle fusion to the presynaptic membrane.

label.value: positive regulation of synaptic vesicle fusion to presynaptic active zone membrane

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of synaptic vesicle fusion to the presynaptic membrane.
A chromatophore containing yellow pigment.

definition.value: Note that this term refers to a subcellular structure, and should not be confused with the specialized cells known as xanthophores, which produce yellow pigment and are found in fish and amphibian skin. Note that several terms in the biological process ontology ('xanthophore differentiation ; GO:0050936' and its children) refer to xanthophores in the sense of pigment-producing cells.

value.value: Binding to replication fork barriers, sites that inhibit the progress of replication forks.

label.value: adenylate cyclase-inhibiting opioid receptor signaling pathway

value.value: An adenylate cyclase-inhibiting G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway initiated by an opioid binding to its receptor, and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process.

label.value: regulation of neuronal synaptic plasticity in response to neurotrophin

value.value: The process in which a neurotrophic factor induces neuronal synaptic plasticity, the ability of neuronal synapses to change as circumstances require. They may alter function, such as increasing or decreasing their sensitivity, or they may increase or decrease in actual numbers.
The proteolytic processing of an inactive enzyme to an active form.

The process in which inactive plasminogen is processed to active plasmin. This process includes cleavage at an internal Arg-Val site to form an N-terminal A-chain and C-terminal B-chain held together by a disulfide bond, and can include further proteolytic cleavage events to remove the preactivation peptide.

label.value: killing of cells of another organism

value.value: Any process in an organism that results in the killing of cells of another organism, including in some cases the death of the other organism. Killing here refers to the induction of death in one cell by another cell, not cell-autonomous death due to internal or other environmental conditions.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the formation of a myelin sheath around nerve axons.
Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the formation of a myelin sheath around nerve axons.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the formation of a myelin sheath around nerve axons.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a neurophysiological process, an organ system process carried out by any of the organs or tissues of the nervous system.

label.value: negative regulation of nervous system process

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of a neurophysiological process.

label.value: positive regulation of nervous system process

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of a neurophysiological process.
Any process that affects the structure and integrity of a protein, altering the likelihood of its degradation or aggregation.
Any process that decreases the stability of a protein, making it more vulnerable to degradative processes or aggregation.
Any homeostatic process in which an organism produces heat, thereby raising its internal temperature.
Any process that modulates the rate or extent of heat generation.
Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the rate or extent of heat generation.
Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of heat generation.
Any homeostatic process in which an organism releases excess heat to the environment, thereby lowering its internal temperature.
Any process that modulates the rate or extent of heat dissipation.
Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the rate or extent of heat dissipation.
Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of heat dissipation.

The series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a lipopolysaccharide (LPS) to a receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription. Lipopolysaccharides are major components of the outer membrane of Gram-negative bacteria, making them prime targets for recognition by the immune system.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of signaling in response to detection of lipopolysaccharide.

label.value: negative regulation of lipopolysaccharide-mediated signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of signaling in response to detection of lipopolysaccharide.

label.value: positive regulation of lipopolysaccharide-mediated signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of signaling in response to detection of lipopolysaccharide.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus reflecting the presence, absence, or concentration of nutrients.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus reflecting the presence, absence, or concentration of nutrients.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a nutrient stimulus.
A cellular process that results in the biosynthesis of constituent macromolecules, assembly, and arrangement of constituent parts of a primary cell septum following nuclear division.
The dark-staining region of a sarcomere, in which myosin thick filaments are present; the center is traversed by the paler H zone, which in turn contains the M line.

A relatively pale zone traversing the center of the A band of a sarcomere, visible in relaxed muscle fibers; consists of the central portion of thick (myosin) filaments that are not overlapped by thin (actin) filaments.

A region of a sarcomere that appears as a light band on each side of the Z disc, comprising a region of the sarcomere where thin (actin) filaments are not overlapped by thick (myosin) filaments; contains actin, troponin, and tropomyosin; each sarcomere includes half of an I band at each end.
The pigmented membrane of a plasma membrane-derived thylakoid.
The heterodimer formed by the beta and gamma subunits of a heterotrimeric G protein, which dissociates from the alpha subunit upon guanine nuclotide exchange.

definition.value: See also the cellular component term 'heterotrimeric G-protein complex ; GO:0005834'.

value.value: Binding to a G-protein beta subunit.
Binding to a G-protein gamma subunit.
Binding to a complex of G-protein beta/gamma subunits.
Binding to an adenosine receptor.
Binding to an A1 adenosine receptor.
